class="headline-container"><h1 class="headline" itemprop="headline"><a
href="http://form.guide/html-form/html-select-multiple.html" rel="bookmark">How to create a select box with multiple selection</a></h1><div
class="byline"><p
class="post_cats" itemprop="keywords">
<a
href="http://form.guide/category/html-form" rel="category tag">HTML Forms</a></p><p
class="post_tags" itemprop="keywords">
<a
href="http://form.guide/tag/html-select-multiple" rel="tag">html select multiple</a></p></div>
</header><div
class="post_content" itemprop="articleBody"><p>Having drop downs on our web page enhances the overall quality and design on the screen.</p><p>A drop-down thus works as an alternative and in specific cases, a better option, as compared to radio buttons and checkboxes.<br
/>
Wait, what? Did we say an alternative to both radio buttons and checkboxes? But, it should have been just the radio button, shouldn’t it?</p><p>A radio button does not allow more than one selections and a checkbox, on the other hand, allows one or more than one selections. A user can select only one option from a drop-down list and therefore it resembles just the radio button in its functionality and not the checkboxes, right? Well, this is where the concept of multiple selections in a select box comes into play.</p><h2>How can I allow users to select multiple options from a select box?</h2><p>From a web designer’s perspective, allowing the user to choose multiple options from a select box is fairly simple and straightforward. We just need to add the &#8220;multiple&#8221; attribute to the &lt;select&gt; element.<br
/>
Now, in order to select multiple options, you have to add a size attribute also to the select element. This will make the select box look like a box rather than just the drop down.</p><p>The user has to hold down the Ctrl key (in Windows) and Command key (on Mac) to select the choices.</p><p></p><div
