<header
class="headline-container"><h1 class="headline" itemprop="headline"><a
href="http://form.guide/best-practices/validate-email-address-using-javascript.html" rel="bookmark">How to validate an email address using JavaScript</a></h1><div
class="byline"><p
class="post_cats" itemprop="keywords">
<a
href="http://form.guide/category/best-practices" rel="category tag">Best Practices</a></p><p
class="post_tags" itemprop="keywords">
<a
href="http://form.guide/tag/email-validation-regex" rel="tag">email validation regex</a>,
<a
href="http://form.guide/tag/email-validation-regular-expression" rel="tag">email validation regular expression</a>,
<a
href="http://form.guide/tag/javascript-email-validation" rel="tag">javascript email validation</a>,
<a
href="http://form.guide/tag/php-email-validation" rel="tag">php email validation</a></p></div>
</header><div
class="post_content" itemprop="articleBody"><p>Validating email address using regular expressions is tricky and is often not recommended. The reason is simple. A valid email address as defined by  <a
href="https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2822#section-3.4.1">RFC 2822</a> can be quite complex.</p><p>A valid email is of the format:<br
/>
name@domain</p><p>The name can be a set of &#8216;atoms&#8217; separated by dots. In its simplest form like this:<br
/>
john.doe@domain</p><p>now, the atoms can contain<br
/>
1. alpha-numeric characters<br
/>
2. Any of these characters<br
/>
<code>! $ &amp; * - = \^ ` | ~ # % ‘ + / ? _ { }</code><br
/>
3. single or double quotes and any character inside the quotes</p><p>Now, to the domain part.<br
/>
Most email validation checks assumes that the top level domain can have up to 4 characters. It is not true. There are TLDs like this: .MUSEUM .travel, .international or even .vermögensberatung</p><p>For example all the following email addresses are valid:</p><ul><li>あいうえお@a.long.domain.example.university</li><li>one.“more\ long”@example.website.place</li><li>customer/department@example.com</li></ul><p>Writing a email validation that validates for all those cases is difficult but possible.<br
/>
Here is an email suggested from this post:</p><h2>A near perfect Javascript Email validation regex</h2><p></p><div
